Regression and model validation

In this exercise, linear regression analysis is used to find out significant predictors of exam points of a statistics course exam.

Data

The data used in the analysis contains 166 cases and 7 variables. Variables “deep”, “stra”, and “surf” are combined variables indicating respondent’s learning strategies: deep, strategic and surface learning. “Attitude” indicates global attitude towards statistics, and “Points” indicates respondent’s exam points. In addition, age and gender are used as basic sociodemographic variables. Descriptive statistics of the data are displayed on the table above. There are considerably more females on the data: 110 vs. 56 males. As for learning strategies, the respondents tend to have slightly higher overall score on deep learning than other strategies.

Initial regression model

Initially, linear regression model is built with three explanatory variables: attitude, age and deep learning. The results of the analysis are displayed on the matrix below. Regarding the explanatory variables, only attitude is statistically significant (p<0.001) with beta-value of 3.59 indicating that increase of one unit of attitude increases the exam points by 3.59 in the model.

my_model1 <- lm(Points ~ Attitude + Age + deep, data = analysis_data)

Fitted regression model

In the fitted linear regression model, age and deep learning are removed from the analysis as non-significant. In this model, attitude remains statistically significant (p<0.001) beta-value being 3.52. The r-square value of 0.19 indicates that the model explains about 19 % of the variability of the dependent “points” variable.

my_model2 <- lm(Points ~ Attitude, data = analysis_data)

The plots below can be interpreted to demonstrate how well the model fits the data. In the QQ-plot (down left), the points seem to follow the line quite well, which indicates that the errors of the model are quite normally distributed. There does not seen to be any patterns on the scatter plot of fitted values and residuals, which indicates that the errors in the model have constant variance. In the residuals vs. leverage plot there is no single observation standing out, which means that there are no observations having an unusually high impact. Based on these plots, the model seems to fit the data quite well.

plot(my_model2, which = c(1, 2, 5), par(mfrow = c(2,2)))

Logistic regression

In this exercise, logistic regression is used to define predictors of alcohol consumption among portuguese students.

Data

The data used in the analysis contains 382 observations and 35 variables related to family, freetime and school. The names of the variables are displayed in the matrix below.

Hypotheses

Before the analysis, four hypotheses are made: 1) Male gender is a statistically significant predictor of high alcohol consumption. 2) Being in a relationship is a statistically significant predictor of high alcohol consumption. 3) Having a lot of school absences predicts high alcohol consumption on a statistically significant level. 4) Going out with friends a lot predicts high alcohol consumption on a statistically significant level.

Analysis

Initial analysis

Initially, all the four predictors described above are used as predictors of high alcohol consumption in a logical regression model.

m <- glm(high_use ~  romantic + goout + sex + absences, data = alc, family = "binomial")
summary(m)

The results show that relationship status is not a statistically significant predictor, and thus the second hypothesis is rejected as false. The variable is removed from the analysis and the model is fitted with three predictors: going out, gender and absences.

Fitted model

m2 <- glm(high_use ~ goout + sex + absences, data = alc, family = "binomial")
summary(m2)

In the second model, all the three predictors are statistically significant (p<0.001). The odd ratios (OR) below are interpreted to understand the results and to varify or falsify the three remaining hypotheses:

  1. The first hypothesis seems to be true: male gender is a statistically significant predictor of high alcohol consumption. Compared to females, males have a 2.61 times higher risk of high alcohol consumption.
  2. The third hypothesis is varified as well: having a lot of school absences predicts high alcohol consumption on a statistically significant level with an odd ratio of 1.09. This means, for example, that having ten more absences increases risk of high alcohol consumption by 2.32 times.
  3. Also, the fourth hypothesis is varified: going out with friends a lot predicts high alcohol consumption on a statistically significant level with an odd ratio of 2.07. Thus, those going out most (5) have a 18.5 times higher risk of high alcohol consumption compared to those who go out least (1).
OR <- coef(m2) %>% exp

CI <- confint(m2) %>% exp

cbind(OR, CI)
##                     OR       2.5 %     97.5 %
## (Intercept) 0.01555815 0.005885392 0.03804621
## goout       2.07468346 1.650182481 2.64111050
## sexM        2.60835292 1.593132148 4.33151387
## absences    1.08782902 1.042458467 1.13933894

Testing the model

The predictive power of the model is tested. With the code below, variable “probability”, indicating the probability of high alcohol cosumption being true according to the model, and variable “prediction” indicating that according to the model there is more than a 50 % chance of high alcohol cosumption being true, are added to the data.

Real values vs. predicted values

The cross-tabulation matrix below shows that 302 of 382 observations in the data ( 79 %) are correctly classified. The plot below visualizes this.

probabilities <- predict(m2, type = "response")

alc <- mutate(alc, probability = probabilities)

alc <- mutate(alc, prediction = (probability > 0.5))

table(high_use = alc$high_use, prediction = alc$prediction)
##         prediction
## high_use FALSE TRUE
##    FALSE   253   15
##    TRUE     65   49
g <- ggplot(alc, aes(x = probability, y =high_use , col = prediction))
g + geom_point()

Classification error

The result of using a loss function on the model shows that there is a 0.21 classification error in the model meaning that the model classifies uncorrectly 21 % of the cases. When guessing that there is a 0.4 chance for every observation in the data to have high alcohol consumption, the error is 30 %. Thus, the model works slightly better than a guess.

loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}

loss_func(class = alc$high_use, prob = alc$probability)
## [1] 0.2094241
alc$guess <- 0.4
loss_func(class = alc$high_use, prob = alc$guess)
## [1] 0.2984293

Cross-validation

Finally, the model is tested with cross-validation. The 10-fold cross-validation of the model results in a 0.21 error. Thus, my model seems to be better than the one in DataCamp, woop.

library(boot)
cv <- cv.glm(data = alc, cost = loss_func, glmfit = m2, K = 10)

cv$delta[1]
## [1] 0.2068063

Clustering and classification

In this exercise, linear discriminant analysis (LDA) and k-means clustering are used to classify data based on crime rate and to find clusters in the data.

Data

The data used in this exercise is the Boston dataset from R’s MASS package. The data contains information about housing in the area of Boston and it has 506 observations and 14 variables. The summaries of the variables are displayed in the matrix below and more information about them can be found here.

The correlation matrix demonstrates the relationships between the variables. Some of the variables have a clear positive or negative correlation, which seems obvious based on the nature of the variables. As for the summary matrix, it can be seen that the variables are very differently distributed compared to each other as different units of measurement are, of course, used.

Creating a categorical variable

After scaling, the continuous “crim”, indicating per capita crime rate by town, is recoded into four categories, and the original variable is replaced by the new categorical “crime” variable.

scaled_crim <- boston_scaled$crim
bins <- quantile(scaled_crim)
crime <- cut(scaled_crim, breaks = bins, include.lowest = TRUE)
crime <- factor(crime, labels = c("low", "med_low", "med_high", "high"))
table(crime)
## crime
##      low  med_low med_high     high 
##      127      126      126      127
boston_scaled <- dplyr::select(boston_scaled, -crim)
boston_scaled <- data.frame(boston_scaled, crime)

Linear Discriminant Analysis

Creating train and test sets

Before the analysis, a train set containing 80 % of the observations in the data and a test set with 20 % of the observations are created.

n <- 506
ind <- sample(n,  size = n * 0.8)
train <- boston_scaled[ind,]
test <- boston_scaled[-ind,]

Analysis

Linear discriminant analysis (LDA) is used to find the variables that separate the classes of the categorical “crime” variable. The results of the analysis are displayed below.

The first linear discriminant (LD1) explains 94.6 % of the between-group variance, and interestingly, the variable “rad” indicating accessibility to radial highways seems to have the greatest effect in that discriminant. Other than that, variables “nox” (nitrogen oxides concentration) and “zn” (proportion of residential land zoned for lots over 25,000 sq.ft.) have somewhat big effect on the discriminants.

The plot below visualizes the results of the analysis.

lda.fit <- lda(crime ~ ., data = train)

lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}
classes <- as.numeric(train$crime)

plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2, col = classes, pch = classes)
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 3)

Testing the predictions

The test set is used to test the predictions of the LDA model. The table below displays the actual and predicted classes of the “crime” variable. 75 out of 102 observations (73,5 %) are correctly classified by the model.

lda.pred <- predict(lda.fit, newdata = test)

Clustering by k-means

The original Boston data (with the continuous “crim” variable) is scaled and the Euclidean distances between the observations are counted in order to use the k-means algorithm. After trying with a few different number of clusters, it seems like two clusters separate the data the best. The scatter plot matrix below demonstrates the clusters in two dimensions. It seems like at least variables “tax” and “rad” are clear separators.

boston <- scale(Boston)
boston <- as.data.frame(boston)
dist_eu <- dist(boston)
summary(dist_eu)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.1343  3.4620  4.8240  4.9110  6.1860 14.4000
km <-kmeans(dist_eu, centers = 2)
pairs(Boston, col = km$cluster)

LDA on clusters

In this model, variable “indus” (proportion of non-retail business acres per town) seems to have the biggest effect as a separator.

km2 <-kmeans(dist_eu, centers = 3)

lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

classes2 <- as.numeric(km2$cluster)

plot(lda.fit2, dimen = 2, col = classes2, pch = classes2)
lda.arrows(lda.fit2, myscale = 3)

Dimensionality reduction techniques

In this exercise, dimensionality reduction techniques are used to find components and connections in two different datasets and in that way reduce number of dimensions in them.

Principal component analysis (PCA)

Data

The “human” dataset contains different indicators of human development and gender inequality. In the modified dataset used in the PCA exercise, there are 155 observations (countries) and the following 8 variables:

“eduratio”: famale/male ratio of population with secondary education

“labourratio”: female/male ratio of labour force participation

“life”: life expectancy at birth

“expedu”: expected years of education

“gni”: gross national income (GNI) per capita

“matmort”: maternal mortality ratio

“adobirth”: adolescent birth rate

“parliament”: % of seats in parliament held by women

The summaries of the variables are displayed in the matrix below, and the plot below visualizes the distributions of the variables and displays the correlations between them. There are some rather big and quite obvious positive/negative correlations between some of the variables; for example, life expectancy correlates negatively with maternal mortality whereas expected years of education has a positive correlation with it.

The first component (PC1) that is highly impacted by gross national income (GNI) per capita captures all the variance in the data when PCA is run using non-standardized data. So, the results can be interpreted as GNI explaining all the differences in human development and gender inequality between countries.

Standardized data

Due to scaling, the results of the second analysis are quite different from the first one in which variable “gni” had a great importance because of its large scale compared to the other variables. In the second analysis, the variables have more equal loadings.

The first component (PC1) captures 53.6 % of the variance in the data. As the plot above shows, this component is highly loaded with variables indicating life expectancy, maternal mortality, adolescent birth rate, expected years of education and education ratio between genders. As for the second component (PC2), which captures 16.2 % of the variance, percentage of women in parliament and ratio of women to men in labour force have the greatest impact.

So, one could sum up that the first component is related to health and educational conditions whereas the second one is more about distribution of societal power between genders, and those two are the most influential in explaining the differences in human development and gender inequality between countries. Interestingly, GNI does not have that much importance in the results of this analysis.

Multiple correspondence analysis (MCA)

Data

The data used in MCA exercise is the “the” dataset in R’s FactoMineR package, and it contains 300 observations and variables related to tea drinking habits. Out of the 36 variables in the original dataset, six are used in this exercise. The distributions of those are displayed in the summary matrix and the bar blot below.

data("tea")
keep_columns <- c("sugar", "sex", "breakfast", "friends", "healthy", "feminine")
